Comment: GTA Online makes the company a LOT of money, especially with Shark Cards. Players LIKE US who know how to grind and make money in the game, WE are only a MINORITY of the actual player base. The majority of GTA players for online are casual players who just play with their friends and use shark cards. So cutting off GTA Online would be foolish of Rockstar and Take 2. The next point is that we should expect that like GTA Online's launch there still isn't going to be a lot to do in GTA Online 2 (if that's what it will be called). So we are going to play around with it, get board after 90 days or something and run back to 5 from time to time until they bring out DLCs and add more to do in the game. Plus our characters are starting from scratch. With no businesses to grind I don't see much to do unless they start up giving us a ton of stuff to do. Next point is there are STILL a ton of people who don't have PS5. Not a lot of people are going to buy a PS5 to play ONE GAME when all their friends are still on PS4. GTA Online and GTA Online 2 are still multiplayer games and people want to play with their friends. So people will go back and forth between the 2 games. Like you said there are still people playing GTA 4 online, which is crazy but it is what it is. There are probably many more reasons why they will not yet shut down the servers for GTA Online that we haven't considered. But the number one factor is that GTA Online makes WAY too much money for them to just pull the servers. I don't believe they will add new DLCs and updates or whatever but it's not going anywhere.

Author: @d4nd31o
Comment:
I think the online environment should simply be called GTA.
I also think that recently, adding even longer to production time, that they have been undoing some of the game which was set in place that wouldn't fly so well in the current day. There was rumour(always, of course) of a second type of in-game currency based on crypto and around the time of The Contract title update(with also some evidence of many of these vehicle models being of a far higher resolution than those seen in GTAO) there were several references to NFT and crypto by npc's. My feeling is that at some point in production, when NFT became shown for the joke it was, a bit of backtracking had to be done. I can still see crypto-currency being included but NFT inclusion the Story for sure will not fly today. Hopefully, neither do motorbikes.
Regardless of my ramblings, I can't wait but I happily will. Nobody wants an unfinished game to appear and those folks at R* are the unmatched Masters of their Craft. It simply isn't ready and they have never released a major open World title in their history that wasn't the best in show, by miles. Six will come to reclaim that crown from the reigning Red Dead Redemption World, just as soon as it can. No doubt.

Author: @hytalefanboi7471
Comment:
IMHO the main problem with the oppressor isn't really how futuristic it is; but moreso that it isn't balanced against the rest of the game at all. Compare it for example with the buzzard which is slower, easier to hit and overall way less nimble and compact. So the bike makes it obsolete. 
Something like the atomizer in contrast is clearly strong, but doesn't outperform the normal weapons in every regard because it does something completely different.
Another good example would be the chernobog which isn't that futuristic and actually is balanced, but still doesn't fit with the rest of the game. Robbing a store and then driving away with a MLRS is just nonsensical.
My main point is that R* lacks a clear vision for what gta online should be. Crime syndicate simulator, special agent military game or arcady open world playground(Arena War). Arena War could've actually fit into the game if they didn't allow the vehicles in freemode.
